WEBVTT

00:01.971 --> 00:04.408
BRYAN: <i>Tonight, in their</i>
<i>final</i> Dance Moms <i>sit‐down,</i>

00:04.408 --> 00:05.845
<i>Maddie and Mackenzie are gonna</i>

00:05.845 --> 00:08.049
<i>relive their experience</i>
<i>from the beginning.</i>

00:08.049 --> 00:10.187
ABBY LEE:
<i>Look at that face!</i>

00:10.187 --> 00:11.757
Why did I not just
forget about Maddie

00:11.757 --> 00:14.897
and take you,
move to Hollywood,

00:14.897 --> 00:16.901
<i>and make you</i>
<i>the next actress star?</i>

00:16.901 --> 00:19.105
BRYAN:
<i>The good times,</i>

00:19.105 --> 00:20.608
<i>the not‐so‐good times...</i>

00:20.608 --> 00:22.478
You keep doing it wrong.

00:22.478 --> 00:24.315
You're wasting my time!

00:24.315 --> 00:25.284
BRYAN: <i>...the triumphs...</i>

00:25.284 --> 00:27.522
BOTH:
Abby Lee Dance Company!

00:27.522 --> 00:29.392
BRYAN: <i>...and the heartbreaks.</i>

00:29.392 --> 00:31.062
MADDIE: <i>No, Abby's gonna</i>
<i>freak out on me!</i>

00:31.062 --> 00:32.766
No, no, no!

00:32.766 --> 00:34.368
BRYAN: <i>Abby has been there</i>
<i>through it all,</i>

00:34.368 --> 00:37.174
<i>taking Maddie and Mackenzie</i>
<i>from inexperienced young kids,</i>

00:37.174 --> 00:39.111
<i>to the performers</i>
<i>they are today.</i>

00:39.111 --> 00:41.249
I can't believe that
we've done all that stuff.

00:41.249 --> 00:45.023
BRYAN: <i>Now it's time for</i>
<i>the sisters to leave the nest.</i>

00:45.023 --> 00:46.794
MELISSA: It's been such
a great ride together.

00:46.794 --> 00:49.365
BRYAN: <i>But before they go,</i>
<i>they're going to answer</i>

00:49.365 --> 00:51.135
<i>some of the questions</i>
<i>that the fans have been asking</i>

00:51.135 --> 00:52.572
<i>on social media for years.</i>

00:52.572 --> 00:53.574
ABBY LEE:
<i>If those mothers</i>

00:53.574 --> 00:54.776
are dumb enough
to give me credit

00:54.776 --> 00:56.547
for the whole thing,
I'm taking it.

00:56.547 --> 00:58.016
BRYAN:
<i>And finally, they're gonna</i>

00:58.016 --> 00:59.485
<i>share their honest memories</i>

00:59.485 --> 01:02.191
<i>of dancing for the one</i>
<i>and only Abby Lee Miller.</i>

01:02.191 --> 01:04.028
You got to kiss him.

01:04.028 --> 01:06.132
Who else would make you
do that, though?

01:06.132 --> 01:08.303
Come on.
That's what makes me special.

01:11.744 --> 01:14.650
♪ Livin' on the dance floor. ♪

01:14.650 --> 01:16.019
(both laughing)

01:16.019 --> 01:16.787
Hi, girls.

01:20.695 --> 01:22.599
What?
MADDIE: She just wants

01:22.599 --> 01:25.370
to sit on the end so she doesn't
have to sit next to Abby.

01:25.370 --> 01:28.778
Is there an advantage to sitting
next to Abby or a disadvantage?

01:28.778 --> 01:31.282
Well, she's the favorite,
so she gets to sit next to Abby.

01:31.282 --> 01:32.719
BRYAN: All right, I think
we're just hanging out

01:32.719 --> 01:34.523
for a second
until she gets ready.

01:35.925 --> 01:37.127
Ten minutes?

01:37.127 --> 01:38.831
What is she doing?

01:38.831 --> 01:40.100
Is there any silver earrings
I bought?

01:40.100 --> 01:41.737
Like those cool ones?

01:41.737 --> 01:43.139
No?
BRYAN:
No.

01:43.139 --> 01:44.543
No.

01:44.543 --> 01:45.912
BRYAN: Kids, yeah,
think of the beginning

01:45.912 --> 01:47.281
when we were talking
about doing this special,

01:47.281 --> 01:49.285
you were a little hesitant?
Yeah.

01:49.285 --> 01:50.353
Why was that?

01:50.353 --> 01:51.724
I was scared that Abby
was gonna yell at me.

01:51.724 --> 01:53.126
(chuckles)
Why would she yell at you?

01:53.126 --> 01:54.863
'Cause she yells at me
all the time.

01:54.863 --> 01:56.934
I get yelled at the most.

01:56.934 --> 01:59.405
Faster, faster, faster!
You cannot slow a pee‐wee down.

01:59.405 --> 02:00.608
It looks ridiculous.

02:00.608 --> 02:03.012
If you have to suck a yawn up
one more time,

02:03.012 --> 02:04.148
you're not in the dance.

02:04.148 --> 02:05.484
Am I that boring?

02:05.484 --> 02:07.454
Do I need to scream
a little louder?

02:07.454 --> 02:09.191
You keep doing it wrong.

02:09.191 --> 02:12.431
You're wasting my time.

02:12.431 --> 02:14.770
Mackenzie, your head does not

02:14.770 --> 02:17.074
go down.

02:17.074 --> 02:19.245
What's your expectations
for today?

02:19.245 --> 02:20.581
I hope we just have fun,

02:20.581 --> 02:23.186
and I get a lot
of dirty secrets about Abby.

02:23.186 --> 02:24.556
Like?

02:24.556 --> 02:25.525
Why she always

02:25.525 --> 02:26.827
<i>has her hair in curlers?</i>

02:26.827 --> 02:28.731
MACKENZIE:
<i>Where does she go at night?</i>

02:28.731 --> 02:31.068
MADDIE: <i>She's usually going to,</i>
<i>like, McDonald's or something.</i>

02:32.271 --> 02:34.375
No, that's
literally where she goes.

02:34.375 --> 02:36.880
WOMAN: There's a bag
of earrings.
MAN: Why don't we
take this out and we can do

02:36.880 --> 02:39.218
our final touch‐up with
jewelry out...
Yeah, that's
good. Let's start walkin'.

02:39.218 --> 02:40.755
Is she almost ready?

02:40.755 --> 02:42.759
Really?

02:43.928 --> 02:47.201
Oh, my thighs
are gonna be chafing.

02:47.201 --> 02:48.269
Oh, you look nice.
Hi!

02:48.269 --> 02:50.875
Hi.
Mackenzie, you can't be in it

02:50.875 --> 02:51.810
'cause you don't match us.

02:51.810 --> 02:53.479
Okay.

02:56.385 --> 02:57.789
Do you have a skirt on?
Yeah.

02:57.789 --> 02:59.626
Wow, I've never seen you
in a skirt.

03:00.628 --> 03:02.097
Nice.

03:02.097 --> 03:03.132
(laughs)

03:03.132 --> 03:04.803
BRYAN: Abby, why don't
you tell the girls

03:04.803 --> 03:06.105
why we're here today.

03:06.105 --> 03:07.542
Girls, we're here today

03:07.542 --> 03:09.044
to take a little trip

03:09.044 --> 03:10.681
down memory lane.
This is gonna be

03:10.681 --> 03:14.789
our last hurrah
on television together.

03:14.789 --> 03:16.158
Maybe.

03:16.158 --> 03:19.198
But who knows
what the future holds, right?

03:22.772 --> 03:25.210
How old were you
when you started the ALDC?

03:25.210 --> 03:26.680
I think I was
two or three.

03:26.680 --> 03:29.118
I'm pretty sure.

03:29.118 --> 03:30.287
I was four. Four.
Four?

03:30.287 --> 03:31.657
Maddie and Mackenzie's
dad, Kurt,

03:31.657 --> 03:34.596
went to high school
with me. And...

03:34.596 --> 03:37.267
he knew that my studio was

03:37.267 --> 03:39.071
the best studio
in our town. He knew

03:39.071 --> 03:41.208
that I traveled all over
the country with my students,

03:41.208 --> 03:42.879
that they went
to a lot of competitions,

03:42.879 --> 03:44.415
and that they won.

03:44.415 --> 03:46.887
When it was time to put both of
his daughters into dance class,

03:46.887 --> 03:49.258
he brought them to me.

03:49.258 --> 03:50.995
Maddie made
an incredible first impression.

03:50.995 --> 03:53.199
She walked
into the studio,

03:53.199 --> 03:57.174
and she was
just this cupcake. This...

03:57.174 --> 03:59.378
<i>tiny little body</i>
<i>and this big head</i>

03:59.378 --> 04:00.781
<i>and these gorgeous big eyes.</i>

04:00.781 --> 04:02.451
And you just wanted
to eat her up.

04:02.451 --> 04:05.390
And she looked me in the eye,
and she spoke for herself,

04:05.390 --> 04:08.162
which I loved that her parents
weren't speaking for her.

04:08.162 --> 04:11.402
And she said, "I want
to take tap and hip‐hop."

04:11.402 --> 04:14.274
And I was like, "Uh,
who does this kid think she is?"

04:14.274 --> 04:16.078
I don't even remember that
at all.

04:16.078 --> 04:18.416
Like, I remember me dancing
at the studio,

04:18.416 --> 04:20.654
but I just don't remember me
walking in and, like,

04:20.654 --> 04:22.491
saying that stuff.
BRYAN:
But you let her in

04:22.491 --> 04:24.395
hip‐hop class, right?
Even though she was only four?

04:24.395 --> 04:26.666
ABBY LEE: I said to the teacher,
"You know what?

04:26.666 --> 04:28.837
"Let her take the class.
She's gonna get in there.

04:28.837 --> 04:30.574
"She's not gonna be able
to do it.

04:30.574 --> 04:32.177
She's gonna come out crying."

04:32.177 --> 04:33.847
That's not what happened.

04:33.847 --> 04:37.254
That night, the teacher said,
"Uh, who is that little kid

04:37.254 --> 04:39.124
in my class?" And I thought,
"Ugh, here it comes."

04:39.124 --> 04:40.126
And she's like,

04:40.126 --> 04:42.030
"She was the best one. She is

04:42.030 --> 04:44.869
so smart. She was better
than any of the other kids."

04:44.869 --> 04:47.040
And I went‐‐ ding‐‐

04:47.040 --> 04:48.209
"Maybe I have a star here."

04:48.209 --> 04:49.311
BRYAN: What about your
first memory

04:49.311 --> 04:50.213
of Mackenzie?

04:50.213 --> 04:52.050
I remember the hair,
a lot of hair,

04:52.050 --> 04:53.520
like Goldie Hawn
or something.

04:53.520 --> 04:54.989
Like, big hair.
And those teeth.

04:56.258 --> 04:57.762
I'm sorry,

04:57.762 --> 05:00.233
<i>she just had that whole</i>
<i>little kid thing going on</i>

05:00.233 --> 05:02.137
<i>with the roof of her mouth,</i>
<i>and she was</i>

05:02.137 --> 05:04.576
absolutely adorable.
Well, you were a baby.

05:04.576 --> 05:07.882
Oh, yeah.
Literally.
A toddler. And then

05:07.882 --> 05:09.318
you grew up at the dance studio.

05:09.318 --> 05:11.222
Every day,
you were there.

05:11.222 --> 05:12.324
I just remember

05:12.324 --> 05:14.328
the first day of
<i>Dance Moms,</i> I think

05:14.328 --> 05:16.600
everyone was super excited.
We were like, "We're gonna be

05:16.600 --> 05:18.871
on TV." I had no clue
that we were gonna learn

05:18.871 --> 05:21.242
a new dance every week.
I‐I thought
No, neither did I.

05:21.242 --> 05:22.512
we were just gonna do
the same dance
Neither did I.

05:22.512 --> 05:25.183
at every competition.
I didn't even realize...

05:25.183 --> 05:26.520
I didn't even know
what the show was about.

05:26.520 --> 05:28.624
Yeah, I didn't think it
would just become what

05:28.624 --> 05:31.563
it has been‐‐ about all the moms
fighting and then you

05:31.563 --> 05:32.999
being, like, the main focus.

05:32.999 --> 05:35.403
You think I'm the main focus?
Yeah.

05:35.403 --> 05:36.438
Yes.
No, I‐I
kind of think

05:36.438 --> 05:37.909
you're
the main focus, babe.

05:37.909 --> 05:40.881
No, you're the main focus,
for sure. You just wanted

05:40.881 --> 05:42.184
to hear me say that, didn't you?

05:42.184 --> 05:45.356
Yes! Again and again
and again.

05:45.356 --> 05:47.260
What was going through your mind
during those first six episodes?

05:47.260 --> 05:49.431
I try not to remember

05:49.431 --> 05:52.437
those first
six episodes.
We look completely different.

05:52.437 --> 05:54.274
How 'bout me?
I didn't think I was
You look the most different.

05:54.274 --> 05:56.646
<i>ever going to be on television</i>
<i>with that hair</i>

05:56.646 --> 05:57.848
<i>and the makeup. I never</i>

05:57.848 --> 06:00.019
<i>thought anybody</i>
<i>was gonna watch this show.</i>

06:00.019 --> 06:02.390
I would have done my hair
and my makeup. I would have

06:02.390 --> 06:04.228
worn something better.

06:04.228 --> 06:05.764
I was just
in there trying

06:05.764 --> 06:06.866
to get routines finished

06:06.866 --> 06:08.202
and choreograph stuff.

06:08.202 --> 06:12.177
And all I knew is
this might be

06:12.177 --> 06:15.951
a chance
to do something wonderful.

06:15.951 --> 06:18.389
So, let's take a look
at what you all looked like

06:18.389 --> 06:20.026
during season one.

06:20.026 --> 06:22.230
These are my two daughters,
Maddie and Mackenzie.

06:22.230 --> 06:25.470
Maddie's eight and Mackenzie's
six. And they're both dancers.
Look at you. Look at that face!

06:25.470 --> 06:31.048
<i>Maddie has won everything that</i>
<i>she's done in the last year.</i>

06:31.048 --> 06:33.419
<i>She was undefeated last year.</i>
(laughter)

06:33.419 --> 06:37.160
<i>Her whole life revolves</i>
<i>around dance.</i>

06:37.160 --> 06:38.897
<i>It's constant.</i>
<i>But she loves it.</i>

06:38.897 --> 06:42.672
You can do cartwheels
all around the room.
I don't care. You always tap.

06:42.672 --> 06:44.207
<i>Abby is a star‐maker.</i>
<i>She's gonna</i>

06:44.207 --> 06:46.880
make my daughter be the best
she can be.

06:46.880 --> 06:49.519
And she will make her a star.

06:49.519 --> 06:51.690
Mackenzie,
that right there...

06:51.690 --> 06:53.760
"You always tap."
See, why did I not

06:53.760 --> 06:56.599
just forget about Maddie
and take you,

06:56.599 --> 06:59.872
move to Hollywood, and make you
the next actress star.

06:59.872 --> 07:01.442
Look at that face!

07:01.442 --> 07:02.812
(laughs)

07:02.812 --> 07:05.350
So, throughout
our time together today, uh,

07:05.350 --> 07:07.454
you guys are gonna be answering
some fan questions.

07:07.454 --> 07:10.627
So, right on the table in front
of you are fan questions.

07:10.627 --> 07:12.631
So whenever you're feeling it,
I want you to reach over,

07:12.631 --> 07:13.834
grab a question.

07:13.834 --> 07:14.736
Go ahead, Mackenzie.

07:18.610 --> 07:20.714
(chuckles)

07:20.714 --> 07:22.551
ABBY LEE:
<i>Pyramid is</i>

07:22.551 --> 07:23.185
grueling.

07:23.185 --> 07:24.522
Seriously.

07:24.522 --> 07:27.260
On <i>Dance Moms,</i> pyramid is

07:27.260 --> 07:29.364
two minutes long.
Not even.

07:29.364 --> 07:31.268
But, actually,

07:31.268 --> 07:33.840
<i>it's four hours long.</i>

07:33.840 --> 07:37.380
(clock ticking)

07:37.380 --> 07:39.384
ABBY LEE: <i>I see you laughing</i>
<i>all the time and talking</i>

07:39.384 --> 07:41.689
<i>and everybody's eyes wandering.</i>

07:41.689 --> 07:43.292
<i>Fingers in the mouth.</i>

07:43.292 --> 07:44.962
<i>Oh, I see it all. I see it all.</i>

07:44.962 --> 07:48.737
MACKENZIE: <i>Once you take off</i>
<i>the paper, you say,</i>

07:48.737 --> 07:50.473
<i>"You're on the bottom</i>
<i>because of your mom."</i>

07:50.473 --> 07:52.477
<i>And then the moms get crazy.</i>

07:52.477 --> 07:54.381
(audio fast‐forwarding)

07:54.381 --> 07:56.485
<i>And then it just takes longer.</i>

07:56.485 --> 07:58.557
MADDIE: <i>Sometimes we'll take</i>
<i>breaks, we'll leave,</i>

07:58.557 --> 08:00.293
<i>we'll come back and finish it.</i>

08:00.293 --> 08:01.830
MACKENZIE: <i>And then, like,</i>
<i>someone either walks out</i>

08:01.830 --> 08:03.567
<i>or you walk out. And then</i>
<i>we don't finish pyramid.</i>

08:03.567 --> 08:06.138
<i>And then we just look</i>
<i>at the pictures.</i>

08:06.138 --> 08:08.142
<i>We can't even talk.</i>
<i>We can't say anything.</i>

08:08.142 --> 08:09.612
MADDIE: <i>We sit there</i>
<i>for four hours doing...</i>

08:09.612 --> 08:11.583
ABBY LEE:
<i>Well, that's the thing is</i>

08:11.583 --> 08:14.522
<i>you can't sit there.</i>
<i>You have to stand.</i>
(bell dings)

08:14.522 --> 08:16.325
That's why I liked
the old pyramid.
And a dancer doesn't like

08:16.325 --> 08:18.429
to stand. What was
the old pyramid?
That's why I
liked the first season.

08:18.429 --> 08:19.732
<i>Because we got to sit</i>
<i>on the floor.</i>
<i>We got to sit on the floor.</i>

08:19.732 --> 08:21.769
ABBY:
<i>Oh...</i>
<i>And we got to stretch</i>

08:21.769 --> 08:23.874
while we were sitting
there.
Well, yes. That was better.

08:23.874 --> 08:26.345
Abby, talk about the first
pyramid. Do you remember it?

08:26.345 --> 08:29.585
The very first pyramid
was a chalkboard. Seriously.

08:29.585 --> 08:32.223
MADDIE:
<i>And your chalk broke.</i>
ABBY LEE: <i>Yeah, the chalk</i>

08:32.223 --> 08:34.327
<i>would break, it would screech,</i>
<i>I would get chills.</i>

08:34.327 --> 08:36.231
It was horrible.
I do remember physically

08:36.231 --> 08:38.402
turning the chalkboard around

08:38.402 --> 08:39.805
because the wheels
were broken,

08:39.805 --> 08:41.308
<i>and one of them fell off</i>

08:41.308 --> 08:44.715
<i>and we had to, like,</i>
<i>lift it up and flip it around.</i>

08:44.715 --> 08:46.719
Okay, here we go.

08:49.257 --> 08:50.894
Maddie and Mackenzie,
you guys sometimes get annoyed

08:50.894 --> 08:53.365
with Mom during pyramid.
MACKENZIE: I usually get annoyed

08:53.365 --> 08:54.702
by my mom
because she talks

08:54.702 --> 08:57.340
about the other moms
in front of their faces,

08:57.340 --> 08:58.877
and I'm just like,
"Well, you shouldn't do that."

08:58.877 --> 09:00.479
Talk about them behind
their back, Mother!

09:00.479 --> 09:01.983
What's wrong with you?
And not just that.

09:01.983 --> 09:04.889
She goes, "Oh, well,
Maddie does this,

09:04.889 --> 09:07.360
and Mackenzie does this,
and Maddie's amazing."
"Yeah, so Maddie just got this."

09:07.360 --> 09:08.730
Maddie's not gonna
be here tomorrow.

09:08.730 --> 09:12.003
It's the Disney 60th
Anniversary Special.

09:12.003 --> 09:13.005
Maddie's a featured dancer.

09:13.005 --> 09:14.575
Elton John is singing.

09:14.575 --> 09:15.677
BOTH:
Mom!

09:15.677 --> 09:17.013
I'm like, "We don't care, Mom.

09:17.013 --> 09:18.315
And no one else cares either."

09:18.315 --> 09:19.652
And then she talks with
Jill, and she goes...

09:20.854 --> 09:21.856
(giggling loudly)

09:21.856 --> 09:26.666
Our first feud happened in 1994.

09:26.666 --> 09:27.868
Can we demonstrate,
Jill and I?

09:27.868 --> 09:30.272
Give me a stick.

09:30.272 --> 09:31.274
(imitates whip cracking)

09:31.274 --> 09:32.276
Yeah...

09:32.276 --> 09:34.114
Why?! Why?!

09:34.114 --> 09:37.020
Why?! Why...

09:37.020 --> 09:39.592
Yeah, they act like
they're two.
And then
everyone's like, "Shush."

09:39.592 --> 09:41.294
So you don't want her speaking
at all during pyramid.
MADDIE: No.

09:41.294 --> 09:43.933
No.
I don't want her to talk
during pyramid at all.

09:43.933 --> 09:46.204
We don't want to get
yelled at. (laughs)
Yeah.

09:46.204 --> 09:48.208
(laughs)
See, they figured it out.

09:48.208 --> 09:51.248
When the mothers start flapping
the lips, I can't stand it,

09:51.248 --> 09:54.889
and Melissa does it
all the time, and the girls know

09:54.889 --> 09:57.594
if their mother is the one that
causes trouble during pyramid,

09:57.594 --> 10:00.433
they're the ones
that are gonna get...

10:00.433 --> 10:04.207
well, let's just say,
the brunt of my words later on.

10:04.207 --> 10:06.311
BRYAN: Speaking of Melissa's
bad habits‐‐

10:06.311 --> 10:09.117
way back,
you assigned these two a duet.

10:09.117 --> 10:11.054
Do you remember?

10:11.054 --> 10:12.991
You guys are sisters.
It's natural that you would be

10:12.991 --> 10:14.360
put in a routine together.

10:14.360 --> 10:18.335
So I gave you two a routine
called, "Run From Mother."

